   <abstract >An examination of the world through the eyes of a cinephile, Splice is a collection of lyrical and intertextual poems that meditate on identity, artistic inspiration, the evocative power of the visual image, and the paradox of living in a body that is both confining and liberating. Expanding on the ekphrastic tradition, these poems translate the silver screen to the poetic line, using linebreaks, formal topography, and musicality to analogize cinematic elements and celebrate the lasting influence of Hollywood icons like Alfred Hitchcock, Terry Gilliam, Martin Scorsese, Frances McDormand, Tilda Swinton, and Bill Murray. At the same time, they narrate the poet's personal journey as he navigates the physical and mental effects of a rare neurological condition called Chiari Malformation. Bringing attention to this overlooked condition and likening the space of the poem to both the cinematic and surgical theater, Splice celebrates the transformative power of poetry and its penchant for provocative recombinations.</abstract>
